# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-revolution
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] The **11 September 1922 Revolution** (Greek: Επανάσταση της 11ης Σεπτεμβρίου 1922) was an uprising by the Greek Army and Navy against the government in Athens, which installed a "Revolutionary Committee" in its place.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] The uprising took place on 24 September 1922, although the date was "11 September" on the Julian calendar still in use at the time in Greece.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] The Greek Army had just been defeated in the Asia Minor Campaign and had been evacuated from Anatolia to the Greek islands in the eastern Aegean.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] Discontent among the middle-ranking officers and men for the campaign's conduct by the royal government boiled over into armed revolt led by pro-Venizelist and anti-royalist officers.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] The mutiny spread quickly and seized power in Athens, forcing King Constantine I to abdicate and leave the country, with a military government ruling the country until early 1924, shortly before the Greek monarchy was abolished and the Second Hellenic Republic established.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] The defeat of the Greek forces in Anatolia had alarmed the people and caused them to ask for the punishment of those responsible for the defeat.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] The government of Petros Protopapadakis resigned and on 28 August, the new government headed by Nikolaos Triantafyllakos.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] On 11 September a revolution was declared, with the formation of a Revolutionary Committee headed by Colonel Nikolaos Plastiras as representative of the army in Chios, Colonel Stylianos Gonatas as representative of the army in Lesvos and Commander Dimitrios Fokas as representative of the navy.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] The next day, the troops boarded their ships and headed to Athens.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] On 13 September, the ships with the Greek army arrived in Lavrio and the next day, King Constantine resigned and went into exile in Italy.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] On 15 September, the troops of revolution entered the city of Athens and blocked the efforts Theodoros Pangalos was making to take advantage of the situation and take control of the government.
[src:american-revolution/11-september-1922-revolution] Soon a new government was formed, with Sotirios Krokidas as chairman.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The **14 July Revolution**, also known as the **1958 Iraqi military coup**, was a military coup that took place on 14 July 1958 in Iraq, resulting in the toppling of King Faisal II and the overthrow of the Hashemite-led Kingdom of Iraq.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi Republic established in its wake ended the Hashemite Arab Federation between Iraq and Jordan that had been established just six months earlier.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Kingdom of Iraq had been a hotbed of Arab nationalism since the Second World War.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Unrest mounted amid economic malaise and widespread disapproval of Western influence, which was exacerbated by the formation of the Baghdad Pact in 1955, as well as Faisal's support of the British-led invasion of Egypt during the Suez Crisis.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Prime Minister Nuri al-Said's policies were unpopular, particularly within the military ranks.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Opposition groups began to organize in secret, modelling themselves after the Egyptian Free Officers Movement that overthrew the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Pan-Arabic sentiment in Iraq was further bolstered by the creation of the United Arab Republic in February 1958 under the leadership of Gamal Abdel Nasser, a staunch proponent of anti-imperialist causes.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] In July 1958, units of the Royal Iraqi Army were dispatched to Jordan in support of King Hussein.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] A group of Iraqi Free Officers, led by Brigadier Abdul-Karim Qasim and Colonel Abdul Salam Arif, took advantage of the opportunity and instead marched on Baghdad.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] On 14 July, revolutionary forces seized control of the capital and proclaimed a new republic, headed by a Revolutionary Council.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] King Faisal and Crown Prince Abd al-Ilah were executed at the royal Al-Rehab Palace, bringing an end to the Hashemite dynasty in Iraq.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Prime Minister al-Said attempted to flee but was captured and shot a day later.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] After the coup, Qasim assumed the position of Prime Minister and Minister of Defence, while Arif was named Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of the Interior.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] A provisional constitution was adopted in late July.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] By March 1959, the new Iraqi government had withdrawn from the Baghdad Pact and aligned itself with the Soviet Union.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] During the Second World War, Iraq was home to a growing number of Arab nationalists.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] They aimed, in part, to remove British imperial influence in Iraq.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] This sentiment grew from a politicised educational system in Iraq and an increasingly assertive and educated middle class.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The two directors of the educational system in Iraq, Sami Shawkat and Fadhil al-Jamal, employed teachers who were political refugees from Palestine and Syria.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] These exiles fled to Iraq because of their roles in anti-British and anti-French protests, and subsequently fostered Arab nationalist consciousness in their Iraqi students.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The growing general awareness of Arab identity led to anti-imperialism.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Similarly, Pan-Arab sentiment grew across the Arab world and was promoted by Egypt's Gamal Abdel Nasser, a rising politician and staunch opponent of imperialism.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Hashemite Iraq faced and confronted these sentiments as well.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Nuri al-Said, the Iraqi Prime Minister during most of the 1930s, 1940s and 1950s, was interested in pursuing the idea of a federation of Arab States of the Fertile Crescent, but was less enthusiastic about a Pan-Arab state.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said brought Iraq into the Arab League in 1944, seeing it as a forum for bringing together the Arab states while leaving the door open for a possible future federation.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The League's charter enshrined the principle of autonomy for each Arab state and referenced pan-Arabism only rhetorically.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi economy fell into a recession and then a depression following the Second World War; inflation was uncontrolled and the Iraqi standard of living fell.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said and the Arab Nationalist regent, Abd al-Ilah, were continually in opposition to each other, failing to agree on a cohesive economic policy, infrastructure improvements, or other internal reforms.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] In 1950, al-Said persuaded the Iraqi Petroleum Company to increase the royalties paid to the Iraqi government.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said looked to the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq's growing oil revenues to fund and propel development.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] He determined that 70 percent of Iraq's revenue from oil was to be set aside for infrastructure development by a Development Board with three foreign advisors out of six total members.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] This foreign presence provoked popular disapproval of al-Said's policy.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Despite anti-Western sentiments toward oil and development, al-Said hired Lord Salter, a British economist and former politician, to investigate the prospects for development in Iraq because al-Said's oil revenue reallocation seemed to be ineffective.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Lord Salter continued to make suggestions as to how to implement development projects despite massive Iraqi dislike of his presence.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] During the Second World War, the British reoccupied Iraq.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] In 1947 prime minister Salih Jabr negotiated British withdrawal, formalised on 15 January 1948 by the Anglo-Iraqi Treaty (also known as the Portsmouth Treaty).
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] This agreement included a British and Iraqi joint defence board to oversee Iraqi military planning, and the British continued to control Iraqi foreign affairs.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Iraq was still tied to Great Britain for military supplies and training.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] This 25-year treaty was to last until 1973—a duration that Arab nationalists in the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq could not accept.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] As a strong reaction to the Anglo-Iraqi Treaty of 1948, Arab nationalists led the Wathbah Rebellion a year later in protest of the continued British presence in Iraq.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said repudiated the Portsmouth Treaty to appease the rebellious Iraqi and Arab nationalists.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] In 1955, Iraq entered into the Baghdad Pact with Iran, Pakistan, and Turkey.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The pact was a defence agreement between the four nations and was endorsed by the UK and the United States as an anti-communist Cold War strategy, but was greatly resented by Iraqis in general.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Egypt saw the Baghdad Pact as a provocation and a challenge to its regional dominance.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] In 1956, when Egypt nationalised the Suez Canal, Iraqi-Egyptian relations were further strained.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] When British, French and Israelis invaded Egypt, Iraq, as a British ally, had to support the invasion.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The fact that imperial ties dragged Iraq into supporting this invasion of Arab lands led to wide disapproval across the Iraqi populace, which largely sympathised with Egypt and responded to pan-Arab ideology.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] It felt that the invasion of Egypt was another sign of Western aggression and dominance in the region.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Similarly, when Egypt and Syria united to form the United Arab Republic (UAR) under the banner of pan-Arabism in 1958, Iraqi politicians found themselves in a vulnerable position.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Iraqi leaders had no interest in uniting with Egypt and instead proposed and ratified their own pan-Arab union with Hashemite Jordan in May 1958.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Great Britain and the United States openly supported this union, but many Iraqis were suspicious of its purpose and regarded the Hashemite Arab Federation as another "tool of their Western overlord".
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The primary goal of the coup was to liberate Iraq from its imperial ties with the British and the United States.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Western powers dominated all sectors of Iraqi governance: national politics and reform, regional politics with its Arab and non-Arab neighbours, and economic policies.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] As a general rule, many Iraqis were resentful of the presence of Western powers in the region, especially the British.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Furthermore, Hashemite monarchic rule could not be divorced from the image of imperial masters behind the monarchy.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The monarchy had struggled to maintain power during the Al-Wathbah uprising in 1948 and the Iraqi Intifada of 1952.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] A growing number of educated élites in the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq were becoming enamoured with the ideals espoused by Nasser's pan-Arab movement.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The ideas of **qawmiyah** (Nationalism) found many willing adherents, particularly within the officer classes of the Iraqi military.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said's policies were considered anathema by certain individuals within the Iraqi armed forces, and opposition groups began to form, modelled on the Egyptian Free Officers Movement that had overthrown the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Despite al-Said's efforts to quell growing unrest within the military ranks (such as economic programmes designed to benefit the officer class, and brokering deals with the U.S. to supply the Iraqi military), his position was significantly weakened by the events of the Suez Crisis.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said suffered for his association with Britain; the latter's role in the Crisis seeming a damning indictment of his **wataniyah** policies.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Despite al-Said's efforts to distance himself from the crisis, the damage was done to his position.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Iraq became isolated within the Arab world, as highlighted by its exclusion from the "Treaty of Arab Solidarity" in January 1957.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Suez Crisis benefited Nasser's pan-Arab cause while simultaneously undermining those Arab leaders who followed pro-Western policy.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said's policies fell firmly within the latter camp, and covert opposition to his government steadily grew in the wake of Suez.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] On 1 February 1958, Egypt and Syria boosted the pan-Arab movement immeasurably with the announcement that they had united as the United Arab Republic (UAR).
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The move was a catalyst for a series of events that culminated in revolution in Iraq.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The formation of the UAR and Nasser's lofty rhetoric calling for a united Arab world galvanised pan-Arabism in both the Hashemite Kingdom of Iraq and the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Their governments attempted something of a response with the creation of the Hashemite Arab Federation on 14 February—a union of the two states—but few were impressed by this knee-jerk reaction to the UAR.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Mutawakkilite Kingdom of Yemen (North Yemen) joined the UAR soon after its formation.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Attention then shifted to Lebanon, where Syria sponsored the Arab nationalist movement in its civil war campaign against the pro-Western government of Camille Chamoun.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said recognised that Chamoun's defeat would leave Iraq and Jordan isolated.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] He bolstered Chamoun's government with aid throughout May and June 1958.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] More fatefully, he attempted to bolster Jordan with units from the Royal Iraqi Army, a move that was a direct catalyst for the *coup d'état*.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] On 14 July 1958, a group that identified as the Free Officers, a secret military group led by Brigadier Abdul-Karim Qasim, overthrew the monarchy.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] This group was markedly Pan-Arab in character.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] King Faisal II, Prince Abd al-Ilah, and Nuri al-Said were all killed.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers were inspired by and modelled after the Egyptian Free Officers who overthrew the Egyptian monarchy in 1952.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] They represented all parties and cut across political factions.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Qasim was a member of the generation that had launched the revolution in Egypt, and had grown up in an era where radicalism and pan-Arabism were circulating in schools, including high schools and military academies.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] As a group, most of the Free Officers were Sunni Arabs who came from a modern middle class.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers were inspired by a number of events in the Middle East the decade before 1952.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The 1948 war against Israel was an experience that intensified the Egyptian Free Officers' sense of duty.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] They understood their mission as deposing the corrupt regimes that had weakened a unified Arab nation and thrown their countries into distress.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The success of the Free Officers in overthrowing the Egyptian monarchy and seizing power in 1952 made Nasser a source of inspiration too.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi Free Officer group was an underground organization, and much of the planning and timing rested in the hands of Qasim and his associate, Colonel Abdul Salam Arif.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Free Officers sought to ensure Nasser's support and the assistance of the UAR to implement the revolt because they feared the members of the Baghdad Pact would subsequently overthrow the Free Officers as a reaction to the coup.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Nasser only offered moral support, whose material significance remained vague, so Egypt had no practical role in the Iraqi revolution.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The dispatching of Iraqi army units to Jordan played into the hands of two of the key members of the Iraqi Free Officers movement: Arif and the movement's leader, Qasim.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Iraqi 19th and 20th Brigades of the 3rd Division (Iraq) (the former under Qasim's command and the latter including Arif's battalion) were dispatched to march to Jordan, along a route that passed Baghdad.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The opportunity for a coup was seized upon by the conspirators.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Arif marched on Baghdad with the 20th Brigade and seized control of the capital, with the help of Colonel Abd al-Latif al-Darraji, while Qasim remained in reserve with the 19th at Jalawla.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] In the early hours of 14 July, Arif seized control of Baghdad's broadcasting station, which was soon to become the coup's headquarters, and broadcast the first announcement of the revolution.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Arif "denounced imperialism and the clique in office; proclaimed a new republic and the end of the old regime...announced a temporary sovereignty council of three members to assume the duties of the presidency; and promised a future election for a new president".
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Arif then dispatched two detachments from his regiment, one to al-Rahab Palace to deal with King Faisal II and the Crown Prince 'Abd al-Ilah, the other to Nuri al-Said's residence.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Despite the presence of the crack Royal Guard at the Palace, no resistance was offered, by order of the Crown Prince.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] It is uncertain what orders were given to the palace detachment, and what level of force they detailed.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] At approximately 8:00 am the King, Crown Prince, Princess Hiyam ('Abd al-Ilah's wife), Princess Nafeesa ('Abd al-Ilah's mother), Princess Abadiya (Faisal's aunt), other members of the Iraqi Royal Family, and several servants were killed or wounded as they were leaving the palace.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Only Princess Hiyam survived, although how and why is unclear.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] With their demise, the Iraqi Hashemite dynasty ended.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Meanwhile, al-Said temporarily slipped the net of his would-be captors by escaping across the Tigris after being alerted by the sound of gunfire.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] By noon, Qasim arrived in Baghdad with his forces and set up headquarters in the Ministry of Defence building.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The conspirators' attention then shifted to finding al-Said, lest he escape and undermine the coup's early success.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] A reward of 10,000 Iraqi dinars was offered for his capture, and a large-scale search began.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] On 15 July he was spotted in a street in the al-Battawin quarter of Baghdad attempting to escape disguised in a woman's abaya.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Al-Said and his accomplice were both shot, and his body was buried in the cemetery at Bab al-Mu'azzam later that evening.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Mob violence continued even in the wake of al-Said's death.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Spurred by Arif to liquidate traitors, uncontrollable mobs took to the streets of Baghdad.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The body of 'Abd al-Ilah was taken from the palace, mutilated and dragged through the streets, and finally hanged outside the Ministry of Defence.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Several foreign nationals, including Jordanian and American citizens, staying at the Baghdad Hotel were killed by the mob.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] A mob invaded the British embassy and set it on fire.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The comptroller of the British ambassador's household, Colonel P.L.Graham MC, was shot dead in the embassy building and his body was never recovered.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Ambassador and other British embassy staff were lucky to escape with their lives.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] After taking refuge in the registry of the embassy, which the mob threatened to burn down, they were escorted to safety by the Iraqi army.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Mass mob violence did not die down until Qasim imposed a curfew, which still did not prevent the disinterment, mutilation and parading of Al-Said's corpse through the streets the day after its burial.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Abdul-Karim Qasim's sudden coup took the U.S. government by surprise.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) Director Allen Dulles told President Dwight D.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Eisenhower that he believed Nasser was behind it.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Dulles also feared that a chain reaction would occur throughout the Middle East and that the governments of Iraq, Jordan, Saudi Arabia, Turkey, and Iran would be doomed.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The Hashemite monarchy represented a reliable ally of the Western world in thwarting Soviet advances, so the coup compromised Washington's position in the Middle East.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Indeed, the Americans saw it in epidemiological terms.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Qasim reaped the greatest reward, being named Prime Minister and Minister of Defence.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Arif became Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of the Interior, and deputy Commander in Chief.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Thirteen days after the revolution, a temporary constitution was announced, pending a permanent organic law to be promulgated after a free referendum.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] According to the document, Iraq was a republic and a part of the Arab nation and the official state religion was listed as Islam.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies were abolished.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Powers of legislation were vested in the Council of Ministers, with the approval of the Sovereignty Council; the executive function was also vested in the Council of Ministers.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] On 9 March 1959, *The New York Times* reported that the situation in Iraq was initially "confused and unstable, with rival groups competing for control.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] The new Iraqi Republic was headed by a Revolutionary Council.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] At its head was a three-man sovereignty council, composed of members of Iraq's three main communal/ethnic groups.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Muhammad Mahdi Kubbah represented the Shi'a population; Khalid al-Naqshabandi, the Kurds; and Najib al Rubay’i, the Sunni population.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] This tripartite council assumed the role of the presidency.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] A cabinet was created, composed of a broad spectrum of Iraqi political movements, including two National Democratic Party representatives, one member of al-Istiqlal, one Ba'ath representative and one Marxist.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] By March 1959, Iraq withdrew from the Baghdad Pact and created alliances with left-leaning countries and communist countries, including the Soviet Union.
[src:american-revolution/14-july-revolution] Because of their agreement with the USSR, Qasim's government allowed the formation of an Iraqi Communist Party.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The **1689 Boston revolt** was a popular uprising on April 18, 1689, against the rule of Sir Edmund Andros, the governor of the Dominion of New England.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] A well-organized "mob" of provincial militia and citizens formed in the town of Boston, the capital of the dominion, and arrested dominion officials.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Members of the Church of England were also taken into custody if they were believed to sympathize with the administration of the dominion.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Neither faction sustained casualties during the revolt.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Leaders of the former Massachusetts Bay Colony then reclaimed control of the government.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] In other colonies, members of governments displaced by the dominion were returned to power.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Andros was commissioned governor of New England in 1686.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He had earned the enmity of the populace by enforcing the restrictive Navigation Acts, denying the validity of existing land titles, restricting town meetings, and appointing unpopular regular officers to lead colonial militia, among other actions.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Furthermore, he had infuriated Puritans in Boston by promoting the Church of England, which was rejected by many nonconformist New England colonists.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] In the early 1680s, King Charles II of England sought to streamline the administration of the American colonies and bring them more closely under crown control.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He revoked the charter of the Massachusetts Bay Colony in 1684, after its leaders refused to act on his demands for reforms in the colony.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Charles died in 1685, but Roman Catholic James II continued the efforts, culminating in his creation of the Dominion of New England.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He appointed former New York governor Sir Edmund Andros as dominion governor in 1686.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The dominion was composed of the territories of the Massachusetts Bay Colony, Plymouth Colony, Connecticut Colony, the Province of New Hampshire, and the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] In 1688, its jurisdiction was expanded to include New York, East Jersey, and West Jersey.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Andros's rule was extremely unpopular in New England.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He disregarded local representation, denied the validity of existing land titles in Massachusetts (which had been dependent on the old charter), restricted town meetings, and forced the Church of England into largely Puritan regions.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He also enforced the Navigation Acts which threatened the existence of certain trading practices of New England.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The royal troops stationed in Boston were often mistreated by their officers, who were supporters of the governor and often either Anglican or Roman Catholic.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Meanwhile, King James became increasingly unpopular in England.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He alienated otherwise supportive Tories with his attempts to relax the Penal Laws, and he issued the Declaration of Indulgence in 1687 which established some freedom of religion, a move opposed by the Anglican church hierarchy.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He increased the power of the regular army, an action seen by many MPs as a threat to their authority, and placed Catholics in important military positions.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] James also attempted to place sympathizers in Parliament who he hoped would repeal the Test Act which required a strict Anglican religious test for many civil offices.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Some Whigs and Tories set aside their political differences when his son and potential successor James was born in June 1688, and they conspired to replace him with his Protestant son-in-law William, Prince of Orange.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The Dutch prince had tried unsuccessfully to get James to reconsider his policies; he agreed to an invasion, and the nearly bloodless revolution that followed in November and December 1688 established William and his wife Mary as co-rulers.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The religious leaders of Massachusetts were led by Cotton and Increase Mather.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] They were opposed to the rule of Andros, and they organized dissent targeted to influence the court in London.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Increase Mather sent an appreciation letter to the king regarding the Declaration of Indulgence, and he suggested to other Massachusetts pastors that they also express gratitude to him as a means to gain favor and influence.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Ten pastors agreed to do so, and they sent Increase Mather to England to press their case against Andros.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Dominion secretary Edward Randolph repeatedly attempted to stop him, including pressing criminal charges, but Mather clandestinely boarded a ship bound for England in April 1688.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He and other Massachusetts agents were received by King James in October 1688, who promised that the colony's concerns would be addressed.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The events of the revolution, however, halted this attempt to gain redress.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The Massachusetts agents then petitioned the new monarchs and the Lords of Trade (predecessors to the Board of Trade that oversaw colonial affairs) for restoration of the Massachusetts charter.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Mather furthermore convinced the Lords of Trade to delay notifying Andros of the revolution.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He had already dispatched a letter to previous colonial governor Simon Bradstreet containing news of a report (prepared before the revolution) that the annulment of the Massachusetts charter had been illegal, and he urged the magistrates to "prepare the minds of the people for a change".
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Rumors of the revolution apparently reached some individuals in Boston before official news arrived.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Boston merchant John Nelson wrote of the events in a letter dated late March, and the letter prompted a meeting of senior anti-Andros political and religious leaders in Massachusetts.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Andros first received a warning of the impending revolt against his control while leading an expedition to fortify Pemaquid (Bristol, Maine), intending to protect the area against French and Indian attacks.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] In early January 1688/9, he received a letter from King James describing the Dutch military buildup.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] On January 10, he issued a proclamation warning against Protestant agitation and prohibiting an uprising against the dominion.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The military force that he led in Maine was composed of regular troops along with Massachusetts and Maine militiamen.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The militia companies were commanded by regulars who imposed harsh discipline that alienated the militiamen they commanded.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Andros was alerted to the meetings in Boston and also received unofficial reports of the revolution, and he returned to Boston in mid-March.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] A rumor circulated that he had taken the militia to Maine as part of a so-called "popish plot;" the Maine militia mutinied, and those from Massachusetts began to make their way home.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] A proclamation reached Boston in early April announcing the revolution; Andros had the messenger arrested, but his news was distributed, emboldening the people.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Andros wrote to his commander at Pemaquid on April 16 that "there is a general buzzing among the people, great with expectation of their old charter", even as he prepared to have the returning deserters arrested and shipped back to Maine.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The threat of arrests by their own colonial militia increased tensions between the people of Boston and the dominion government.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] At about 5 a.m. on April 18, militia companies began gathering outside Boston at Charlestown just across the Charles River, and at Roxbury, located at the far end of the neck connecting Boston to the mainland.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] At about 8 a.m., the Charlestown companies boarded boats and crossed the river while the Roxbury companies marched down the neck and into the city.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Simultaneously, men from the Ancient and Honorable Artillery Company entered the homes of the regimental drummers in the city, confiscating their equipment.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The militia companies met at about 8:30, joined by a growing crowd, and began arresting dominion and regimental leaders.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] They eventually surrounded Fort Mary where Andros was quartered.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Among the first to be arrested was Captain John George of HMS *Rose* who came ashore between 9 and 10 a.m., only to be met by a platoon of militia and the ship's carpenter who had joined the rebelling colonists.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] George demanded to see an arrest warrant, and the militiamen drew their swords and took him into custody.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] By 10 a.m., most of the dominion and military officials had either been arrested or had fled to the safety of Castle Island or other fortified outposts.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Boston Anglicans were rounded up by the people, including a church warden and an apothecary.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Sometime before noon, an orange flag was raised on Beacon Hill signaling another 1,500 militiamen to enter the city.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] These troops formed up in the market square, where a declaration was read which supported "the noble Undertaking of the Prince of Orange", calling the people to rise up because of a "horrid *Popish Plot*" that had been uncovered.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The Massachusetts colonial leadership headed by ex-governor Simon Bradstreet then urged Governor Andros to surrender for his own safety.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He refused and tried to escape to *Rose*, but the militia intercepted a boat that came ashore from *Rose*, and Andros was forced back into Fort Mary.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Negotiations ensued and Andros agreed to leave the fort to meet with the council.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He was promised safe conduct and marched under guard to the townhouse where the council had assembled.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] There he was told that "they must and would have the Government in their own hands", as an anonymous account describes it, and that he was under arrest.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Daniel Fisher Jr., son of Daniel Fisher grabbed him by the collar and took him to the home of dominion official John Usher and held him under close watch.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Fort Mary surrendered on the 19th, and Andros was moved there from Usher's house.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He was confined with Joseph Dudley and other dominion officials until June 7, when he was transferred to Castle Island.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] A story circulated widely that he had attempted an escape dressed in women's clothing.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] This was disputed by Boston's Anglican minister Robert Ratcliff, who claimed that such stories had "not the least foundation of Truth" but were "falsehoods and lies" propagated to "render the Governour odious to his people".
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Andros did make a successful escape from Castle Island on August 2 after his servant bribed the sentries with liquor.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He managed to flee to Rhode Island but was recaptured soon after and kept in what was virtually solitary confinement.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He and others arrested in the wake of the revolt were held for 10 months before being sent to England for trial.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Massachusetts agents in London refused to sign the documents listing the charges against Andros, so he was summarily acquitted and released.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] He later served as governor of Virginia and Maryland.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] The other New England colonies in the dominion were informed of the overthrow of Andros, and colonial authorities moved to restore the governmental structures which had been in place prior to the dominion's enforcement.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Rhode Island and Connecticut resumed governance under their earlier charters, and Massachusetts resumed governance according to its vacated charter after being temporarily governed by a committee composed of magistrates, Massachusetts Bay officials, and a majority of Andros's council.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] New Hampshire was temporarily left without formal government and was controlled by Massachusetts and its governor Simon Bradstreet, who served as *de facto* ruler of the northern colony.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Plymouth Colony also resumed its previous form of governance.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] During his captivity, Andros had been able to send a message to Francis Nicholson, his New York-based lieutenant governor.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Nicholson received the request for assistance in mid-May, but most of his troops had been sent to Maine and he was unable to take any effective action because tensions were also rising in New York.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Nicholson himself was overthrown by a faction led by Jacob Leisler, and he fled to England.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Leisler governed New York until 1691 when a detachment of troops arrived followed by Henry Sloughter, commissioned governor by William and Mary.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Sloughter had Leisler tried on charges of high treason; he was convicted and executed.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] No further effort was made by English officials to restore the shattered dominion after the suppression of Leisler's Rebellion and the reinstatement of colonial governments in New England.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Once Andros' arrest was known, the discussion in London turned to dealing with Massachusetts and its revoked charter.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] This led to formation of the Province of Massachusetts Bay in 1691, merging Massachusetts with Plymouth Colony and territories previously belonging to New York, including Nantucket, Martha's Vineyard, the Elizabeth Islands, and parts of Maine.
[src:american-revolution/1689-boston-revolt] Increase Mather was unsuccessful in his attempts to restore the old Puritan rule; the new charter called for an appointed governor and religious toleration.
[src:american-revolution/1776-book] The text closely mirrors the original book, but omits or summarizes some parts deemed too long.
[src:american-revolution/1776-book] The Illustrated Edition comes with its own protective slipcase, decorated with *The Capture of the Hessians at Trenton, December 26, 1776* by John Trumbull and has a "fake watermark" of the Great Seal of the United States on the back and front.
[src:american-revolution/1776-book] The book is plain covered in blue with the golden embossed numbers "1776".
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:american-revolution/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The state of union is an address, in the United States, given by the president to a joint session of Congress, the United States House of Representatives and United States Senate.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The United States constitution requires the president "from time to time give to the Congress Information of the State of the Union." Today the state of the union address is given as a speech, though this is not a requirement of the constitution.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] George Washington chose to address the Congress in a speech annually; on October 25, 1791, he gave his third speech.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] A major concern at the time was the raising of taxes, as Congress were arguing whether they had the constitutional power to do so.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Revenues for the Federal Government were at that time mostly collected on import duties.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Alexander Hamilton, the then Secretary of the Treasury, felt these had been raised to as high a level as was reasonable, and a new income stream was necessary.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Before the speech, Congress had been debating where to put the capital.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Finally, through a deal made between Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson, they came to a conclusion.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] This deal is known as the Compromise of 1790.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the U.S. was in possession of the original thirteen colonies, along with the land gained in the Treaty of Paris.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The Treaty of Paris ended the revolutionary war; in it, America was granted territory as far west as the Mississippi River.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Known as the year of "Great Immigration" 1788 was the year many Americans moved west.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On October 18, 1790, the Ohio tribe defeated an expedition of American troops near Fort Wayne, Indiana; this signified the beginning of the hostilities in the North West territory.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] On March 30, 1791, construction of the Knoxville Road began, linking to the Wilderness Road and to Knoxville.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The road opened up more frontier area for settlements.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] In September 1791, there was much hostility in Ohio territory; this caused Americans to build forts at Hamilton, St.Clair, Jefferson, Greenville and Recovery.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the time the Census Act had been in place for just over a year and a half.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The act called for a routine census of the United States, and was passed by Congress on March 1, 1790.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He acknowledged that there had been some "degree of discontent" about the Whiskey Tax, and that it was not perfect, but he was going to keep it anyway.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He said "revision of the provision will be found advisable." The Whiskey tax was one Hamilton wanted enacted as part of a funding system for the new country.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the debt has been mostly dealt with, but there might be a few things that still need to be paid off and he urges the House of Representatives to pay off any lingering debts, and there will be exact numbers coming to them soon.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] "The part of the debt of the United States which remains unsubscribed will naturally engage your further deliberation," Washington is saying the House of Representatives must talk further on the debt that has not yet been dealt with.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington briefly mentions the "completion of the census of the inhabitants," he is talking about the Census of 1790.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that "the present population of the United States borders on 4,000,000 persons".
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] The number was 3,929,625 according to the 1790 Census.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] At the end of the speech he comments on "the militia, the post office and post roads, the mint, weights and measures, a provision for the sale of the vacant lands of the United States." Washington wants to send militia to particularly vulnerable places in the US, as they are a new country.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He says that the United States must have "systematic and solid arrangements, exposed as little as possible to the hazards of fortuitous circumstances." He beliefs that there must be more post offices and roads, to create unity with in the country.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] As well to make sure that there is no :misrepresentation and misconception" of the "laws and proceedings of the Government." He then remarks that there is a scarcity of smaller American change and that there must be more put into place.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington then goes on to say that the wright and measures of the country must be uniform and conducive to public convenience.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] Washington spent a good deal of the speech trying to convince the Native Americans to become part of the United States, as well as convincing the citizens of the country of the importance of doing so.
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He pushed the Senate to ratify the treaties pending before that House with the Cherokees and Six Nations of Indians (Iroquois Confederation).
[src:american-revolution/1791-state-of-the-union-address] He stated that the House needed to act on bills to ensure the financial security of the nation.
[src:american-revolution/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The **1792 State of the Union Address** was delivered by George Washington to Congress on Tuesday, November 6, 1792.
[src:american-revolution/1792-state-of-the-union-address] It was presented in Philadelphia's Congress Hall.
[src:american-revolution/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The president commented on continued incursions by Native Americans into frontier settlements.
[src:american-revolution/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Notably, the address contains mention of the Chickamaugas, a part of the Cherokee tribe that committed multiple incursions in frontiers along the Tennessee River.
[src:american-revolution/1792-state-of-the-union-address] The President noted that the incursions were a violation of the Treaty of Holston.
[src:american-revolution/1792-state-of-the-union-address] Still further to promote and secure these inestimable ends there is nothing which can have a more powerful tendency than the careful cultivation of harmony, combined with a due regard to stability, in the public councils.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The **American Revolution** (1765–1789) was a political movement in the Thirteen Colonies of Great Britain.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The movement began as a rebellion and evolved into a revolution resulting in the sovereign United States.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] These changes were the outcome of the associated American Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress, as the provisional government, established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief in 1775.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The following year, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution on July 2nd, then unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence on the Fourth of July.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Throughout most of the war, the outcome appeared uncertain.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] However, in 1781, a decisive victory by Washington and the Continental Army in the Siege of Yorktown led King George III and the Fox–North coalition in government to negotiate the cessation of colonial rule and the acknowledgment of American sovereignty, formalized in the Treaty of Paris in 1783.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Constitution took effect in 1789 and the Bill of Rights was ratified in 1791.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the French and Indian War ended in 1763.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Even though the colonies had fought in and supported the war directly with troops, funds and material, the British Parliament imposed new taxes to ostensibly compensate for wartime costs, and transferred control of the colonies' western lands to British officials in Montreal.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Representatives from several colonies convened in New York City for the Stamp Act Congress in 1765; its "Declaration of Rights and Grievances" argued that this taxation without representation in Parliament and other policies violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, though the Stamp Act was repealed, tensions flared again following Parliament's passage of the Townshend Acts.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In an effort to quell the mounting rebellion, King George III deployed British troops to the colony of Massachusetts, where they killed antagonists in the 1770 Boston Massacre.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In December 1773, the local faction of the colonies-wide Sons of Liberty underground orchestrated the Boston Tea Party, during which they dumped chests of taxed tea owned by the British East India Company into Boston Harbor.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Parliament responded by enacting a series of punitive laws, intended to end self-government in Massachusetts, but instead increased American support for the revolutionary cause.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1774, twelve of the Thirteen Colonies sent delegates to the First Continental Congress; the Province of Georgia joined in 1775.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The First Continental Congress began coordinating Patriot resistance through underground networks of committees largely built on the foundations of the Sons of Liberty network.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In August 1775, King George III proclaimed Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British attempted to disarm the colonists, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, sparking the Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in May of 1775 and created the Continental Army, which then surrounded Boston, forcing the British to withdraw by sea in March 1776 and leaving Patriots in control in every colony.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority, and each colony created a state constitution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On July 2, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution, affirming their support for joint independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On July 4, 1776 they unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence, famously proclaiming that "all men are created equal", having then evolved from a rebellion over British rights to a revolution based on universal rights.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Congress soon after began deliberating the Articles of Confederation, an effort to establish a multi-state self-governing coordinating body capable of negotiating international treaties and prosecuting the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Revolutionary War continued for another five years during which France ultimately entered, supporting the revolutionary cause.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On September 28, 1781, Washington commanded the Continental Army's capture of a British army under General Cornwallis at the Siege of Yorktown, leading to the collapse of King George's control of Parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Consensus in Parliament soon shifted to the war ending on American terms.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On September 3, 1783, the British signed the Treaty of Paris, recognizing the sovereign independence of the United States, and ceding to the new nation nearly all the territory east of the Mississippi River and south of the Great Lakes.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The United States became the first nation to establish a federal republic with a written constitution based on the principles of universal natural rights, consent of the governed, and equality under the law, albeit with significant democratic limitations compared to later evolution of the concept.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution in Great Britain, it unofficially adopted a policy of "salutary neglect," whereby the Thirteen Colonies were largely left to govern themselves.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] This British policy reverted significantly after the French and Indian War.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British political establishment, especially after taking massive swaths of land from the former territories of New France, pursued a policy of greater control over colonial affairs, prompting the Thirteen Colonies to seek restoration of greater autonomy from Britain.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] After the American Revolution one Patriot, Capt.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Levi Preston of Danvers, Massachusetts, who was asked why the Americans rebelled against England, responded: "...we always had governed ourselves, and we always meant to.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies were established in the 17th century as part of the English Empire and became parts of the British Empire after the union of England and Scotland in 1707.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The development of a unique American identity can be traced to the English Civil War (1642–1651) and its aftermath.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In that period the Puritan colonies of New England supported the Commonwealth government responsible for the execution of King Charles I.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] After the Stuart Restoration of 1660, Massachusetts did not recognize Charles II as the legitimate king for more than a year after his coronation.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In King Philip's War (1675–1678), the New England colonies fought a coalition of a few Native American tribes without military assistance from England, thereby contributing to the development of a uniquely American identity separate from that of the British people.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In the 1680s, Charles and his brother, James II, attempted to bring New England under direct English control.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The colonists fiercely opposed this, and the Crown nullified their colonial charters in response.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1686, James finalized these efforts by consolidating the separate New England colonies along with New York and New Jersey into the Dominion of New England.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Edmund Andros was appointed royal governor and tasked with governing the new Dominion under his direct rule.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Colonial assemblies and town meetings were restricted, new local taxes were levied, and rights were abridged.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Dominion rule triggered bitter resentment throughout New England.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] When James tried to rule without Parliament, the English aristocracy removed him from power in the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] This was followed by the 1689 Boston revolt, which overthrew Dominion rule.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Colonial governments reasserted their control after the revolt.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The new monarchs, William and Mary, granted new charters to the individual New England colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution, the British Empire became a constitutional monarchy with sovereignty in the King-in-Parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Aristocrats inherited seats in the House of Lords, while the gentry and merchants controlled the elected House of Commons.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The king ruled through cabinet ministers who depended on majority support in the Commons to govern effectively.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] British subjects on both sides of the Atlantic proudly claimed that the unwritten British constitution, with its guarantees of the rights of Englishmen, protected personal liberty better than any other government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British constitution served as the model for colonial governments.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Crown appointed a royal governor in each colony to exercise executive power, usually also appointing a Governor's Council largely to act as an unelected upper chamber of the legislature.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Property owners elected a colonial assembly amongst themselves with powers to legislate and levy taxes, but the British government reserved the right to veto colonial legislation.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British government lacked the resources and information necessary for close supervision of the colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Instead, British officials negotiated and compromised with colonial leaders to gain compliance with imperial policies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The colonies defended themselves with provincial troops and colonial militias of locals, and the British government rarely sent military forces to America before 1755.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] According to historian Robert Middlekauff, "Americans had become almost completely self-governing" before the American Revolution, a practice that was consistent with the British monarchy's practice of salutary neglect.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] With little industry except shipbuilding, the colonies exported agricultural products in return for manufactured goods.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They also imported molasses, rum, and sugar from the British West Indies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1651, Parliament passed the first in a series of Navigation Acts, which restricted colonial trade with foreign countries.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British government pursued this policy of mercantilism in order to grow its economic and political power.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] According to mercantilism, the colonies existed for the mother country's economic benefit, and the colonists' economic needs were largely inconsequential.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies could trade with the rest of the empire but only ship certain commodities like tobacco to Britain.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Any European imports bound for British America had to first pass through an English port and pay customs duties.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Other laws regulated the developing colonial industries to prevent competition with industries in Britain, such as the Wool Act 1698, the Hat Act 1731, and the Iron Act 1750.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Colonial reactions to these policies were mixed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Molasses Act 1733, for example, placed a duty of six pence per gallon upon foreign molasses imported into the colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] This act was particularly egregious to the New England colonists, who protested it as unconstitutional taxation without representation in the British parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The act increased the smuggling of foreign molasses, and the British government ceased enforcement efforts after the 1740s.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, certain merchants and local industries benefited from the restrictions on foreign competition.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The limits on foreign-built ships greatly benefited the colonial shipbuilding industry, particularly in New England.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Some argue that the economic impact was minimal on the colonists, but the political friction that the acts triggered was more serious, as the merchants most directly affected were also the most politically active.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] During the French and Indian War (1754–1763), the British government fielded 45,000 soldiers, half British Regulars and half colonial volunteers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The colonies also contributed funds and materiel to the war effort; though, two-fifths of this spending was reimbursed by the British government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Great Britain defeated France and acquired that nation's territory east of the Mississippi River.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In order to allow approximately 1,500 politically well-connected British Army officers to remain on active duty in America with full pay after the war, the Bute ministry decided in early 1763 to permanently garrison 10,000 soldiers in North America.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Due to long-established English resistance to a standing army, stationing these officers in Great Britain during peacetime was a politically unacceptable alternative.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The excuse made for a standing army in America was defense against French troops stationed in the West Indies, and foreign populations in newly acquired territories (the French in Canada and the Spanish in Florida).
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In addition, British soldiers were supposed to help collect customs duties and prevent colonists from instigating conflict with Native Americans.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Instead, increased British migration beyond the Appalachian Mountains and Native American anger over the policies of General Jeffery Amherst caused Pontiac's War (1763–1766).
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In response, the Grenville ministry issued the Royal Proclamation of 1763, designating the territory between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River an Indian Reserve closed to colonial settlement.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Proclamation angered settlers, fur traders, and land speculators; however, it failed to stop westward migration.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Stationing troops in North America on a permanent basis would cost another £360,000 a year.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On a per capita basis, Grenville claimed Americans paid 1 shilling in taxes directly to the empire (not including local taxes) compared to 26 shillings paid by the English.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The enslaved, a near majority of the population in some colonies, did not pay any taxes and therefore skewed this comparison.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On March 9, 1764, Grenville proposed the Sugar Act, which was enacted by Parliament in April.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] It lowered the duty on foreign molasses from 6 pence to 3 pence per gallon.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Treasury believed it would generate £78,000.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] To ensure this money could be collected, the act strengthened efforts against smuggling.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials could choose whether to prosecute violators in colonial courts or vice admiralty courts.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Unlike colonial courts where there was a presumption of innocence and cases were decided by local juries who frequently acquitted accused smugglers, vice admiralty courts operated on a presumption of guilt and cases were decided by Crown-appointed judges.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On the same day he introduced the Sugar Act in Parliament, Grenville stated it might be necessary to levy stamp duties on the colonies to raise additional revenue, but he delayed action to give the colonies time to propose another way to raise the revenue.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Parliament passed the Stamp Act in March 1765, which imposed direct taxes on the colonies for the first time.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] All official documents, newspapers, almanacs, and pamphlets were required to have the stamps—even decks of playing cards.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The colonists did not object that the taxes were high; they were actually low.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They objected to their lack of representation in the Parliament, which gave them no voice concerning legislation that affected them, such as the tax, thereby violating the unwritten English constitution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] This grievance was overly simplified with the slogan "No taxation without representation".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Shortly following adoption of the Stamp Act, factions of the Sons of Liberty formed in each colony, and began using public demonstrations, boycotts, and threats of violence to ensure that the offending British policies became unenforceable.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In Boston, the Sons of Liberty burned the records of the vice admiralty court and looted the home of chief justice Thomas Hutchinson.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Several legislatures called for united action, and nine colonies sent delegates to the Stamp Act Congress in New York City in October.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Moderates led by John Dickinson drew up a Declaration of Rights and Grievances stating in part that the colonists were equal to all other British subjects and that, among other abuses, taxes passed without representation in Parliament violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Parliament at Westminster saw itself as the supreme lawmaking authority throughout the Empire and thus entitled to enact any legislation, including levying any tax, without colonial approval or even consultation.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They argued that the colonies were legally British corporations subordinate to the British Parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Parliament insisted that the colonists effectively enjoyed a "virtual representation", as most British people did, since only a small minority of the British population were eligible to elect representatives to Parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] However, Americans such as James Otis maintained that there was no one in Parliament responsible specifically to any colonial constituency, so they were not "virtually represented" by anyone in Parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Rockingham government came to power in July 1765, and Parliament debated whether to repeal the stamp tax or to send an army to enforce it.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin appeared before them to make the case for repeal, explaining that the colonies had spent heavily in manpower, money, and blood defending the empire, and that further taxes to pay for those wars were unjust and might bring about a rebellion.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Parliament agreed and repealed the tax on February 21, 1766, but they insisted in the Declaratory Act of March 1766 that they retained full power to make laws for the colonies "in all cases whatsoever".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The repeal nonetheless caused widespread celebrations in the colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, the British Parliament passed the Townshend Acts, which placed duties on several staple goods, including paper, glass, and tea, and established a Board of Customs in Boston to more rigorously execute trade regulations.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The new taxes were enacted on the belief that Americans only objected to internal taxes and not to external taxes such as custom duties.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] John Dickinson however, in his widely read pamphlet *Letters from a Farmer in Pennsylvania*, argued against the constitutionality of the acts because their purpose was to raise revenue and not to regulate trade.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Colonists responded to the taxes by organizing new boycotts of British goods.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] These boycotts were less effective, however, as the goods taxed by the Townshend Acts were widely used.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In February 1768, the Assembly of Massachusetts Bay Colony issued a circular letter to the other colonies urging them to coordinate resistance.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The governor dissolved the assembly when it refused to rescind the letter.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In June 1768 a riot broke out in Boston over the seizure of the sloop *Liberty*, owned by John Hancock, for alleged smuggling.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials were forced to flee, prompting the British to deploy troops to Boston.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] A Boston town meeting declared that no obedience was due to parliamentary laws and called for the convening of a convention.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] A convention assembled but only issued a mild protest before dissolving itself.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In January 1769, Parliament responded to the unrest by reactivating the Treason Act 1543 which called for subjects outside the realm to face trials for treason in England.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The governor of Massachusetts was instructed to collect evidence of said treason, and the threat caused widespread outrage, though it was not carried out.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On March 5, 1770, a large crowd gathered around a group of British soldiers on a Boston street.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The crowd grew threatening, throwing snowballs, rocks, and debris at them.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] There was no order to fire, but the soldiers panicked and fired into the crowd.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They hit 11 people; three civilians died of wounds at the scene of the shooting, and two died shortly after.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The event quickly came to be called the Boston Massacre.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The soldiers were tried and acquitted (defended by American patriot John Adams), but the widespread descriptions soon began to turn colonial sentiment against the British.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] This accelerated the downward spiral in the relationship between Britain and the province of Massachusetts, and other colonies were becoming increasingly empathetic.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] A new ministry under Lord North came to power in 1770, and Parliament repealed most of the Townshend duties, except the tax on tea.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] This temporarily resolved the crisis, and the boycott of British goods largely ceased, with only the more radical patriots such as Samuel Adams continuing to agitate.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In June 1772, American patriots, including John Brown, burned a British warship that had been vigorously enforcing unpopular trade regulations, in what became known as the *Gaspee* Affair.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The affair was investigated for possible treason, but no action was taken.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1773, private letters were published in which Massachusetts Governor Thomas Hutchinson claimed that the colonists could not enjoy all English liberties, and in which Lieutenant Governor Andrew Oliver called for the direct payment of colonial officials, which had been paid by local authorities.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] This would have reduced the influence of colonial representatives over their government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The letters' contents were used as evidence of a systematic plot against American rights, and discredited Hutchinson in the eyes of the people; the colonial Assembly petitioned for his recall.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin, postmaster general for the colonies, acknowledged that he leaked the letters, which led to him being removed from his position.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] From Boston Samuel Adams set about creating new Committees of Correspondence, built largely on the foundations of the underground Sons of Liberty network, linking Patriots in all 13 colonies and eventually providing the framework for a provisional government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Virginia, the largest colony, set up its Committee of Correspondence in early 1773, on which Patrick Henry and Thomas Jefferson served.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] A total of about 7,000 to 8,000 Patriots served on these Committees; Loyalists were excluded.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The committees became the leaders of the American resistance to British actions, and later largely determined the war effort at the state and local level.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] When the First Continental Congress resolved to boycott British products, the colonial and local Committees took charge, examining merchant records and publishing the names of merchants who attempted to defy the boycott by importing British goods.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, Parliament passed the Tea Act lowering the price of taxed tea exported to the colonies, to help the British East India Company undersell smuggled untaxed Dutch tea.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Special consignees were appointed to sell the tea to bypass colonial merchants.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The act was opposed by those who resisted the taxes and also by smugglers who stood to lose business.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In every colony demonstrators warned merchants not to bring in tea that included the hated new tax.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In most instances, the consignees were forced by the Americans to resign and the tea was turned back, but Massachusetts governor Hutchinson refused to allow Boston merchants to give in to pressure.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] A town meeting in Boston determined that the tea would not be landed, and ignored a demand from the governor to disperse.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On December 16, 1773, a group of men, led by Samuel Adams and dressed to evoke the appearance of Indigenous people, boarded the ships of the East India Company and dumped £10,000 worth of tea from their holds (approximately £636,000 in 2008) into Boston Harbor.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Decades later, this event became known as the Boston Tea Party and remains a significant part of American patriotic lore.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British government responded by passing four laws that came to be known as the Intolerable Acts, further darkening colonial opinion towards England.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The first was the Massachusetts Government Act which altered the Massachusetts charter and restricted town meetings.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The second was the Administration of Justice Act which ordered that all British soldiers to be tried were to be arraigned in Britain, not in the colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The third was the Boston Port Act, which closed the port of Boston until the British had been compensated for the tea lost in the Boston Tea Party.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The fourth was the Quartering Act of 1774, which allowed royal governors to house British troops in the homes of citizens without permission of the owner.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In response, "Starting in August 1774, each time a court was slated to meet in some Massachusetts town, great numbers of angry citizens made sure it did not".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The next month Patriots issued the Suffolk Resolves and formed an alternative shadow government known as the Massachusetts Provincial Congress, which began training militia outside British-occupied Boston.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In September 1774, the First Continental Congress convened in Pennsylvania, consisting of representatives from each colony, to serve as a vehicle for deliberation and collective action.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] During secret debates, conservative Joseph Galloway proposed the creation of a colonial Parliament that would be able to approve or disapprove acts of the British Parliament, but his idea was tabled in a vote of 6 to 5 and was subsequently removed from the record.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Congress called for a boycott beginning on December 1, 1774, of all British goods; it was enforced by new local committees authorized by the Congress that were largely built upon the earlier Committees of Correspondence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] It also began coordinating Patriot resistance by militias in each colony, including many veterans who had gained military experience in the French and Indian War.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] For the first time, the Patriots were armed and unified against Parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] King George III declared Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion in February 1775 and the British garrison received orders to seize the rebels' weapons and arrest their leaders, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Patriots assembled a militia 15,000 strong and laid siege to Boston, occupied by 6500 British soldiers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in Philadelphia on June 14, 1775.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The congress was divided on the best course of action.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They authorized formation of the Continental Army, appointing George Washington as its commander-in-chief, while producing the Olive Branch Petition in which they attempted to come to an accord with King George.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The king, however, would issue a Proclamation of Rebellion in August which declared that all the states were "in rebellion" and the members of Congress were traitors.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, the Battle of Bunker Hill on June 17, 1775 was a British victory—but at a great cost: about 1,000 British casualties from a garrison of about 6,000, as compared to 500 American casualties from a much larger force.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In the winter of 1775, the Americans invaded northeastern Quebec under generals Benedict Arnold and Richard Montgomery, expecting to rally sympathetic colonists there.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The attack was a failure; many Americans were killed, captured, or died of smallpox.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Following the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775, the Patriots had control of Massachusetts outside Boston's city limits, and the Loyalists suddenly found themselves on the defensive with no protection from the British army.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In each of the Thirteen Colonies, American patriots overthrew their existing governments, closed courts, and drove out British colonial officials.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They held elected conventions and established their own legislatures, which existed outside any legal parameters established by the British.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] New constitutions were drawn up in each state to supersede royal charters.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They proclaimed that they were now *states*, no longer *colonies*.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On January 5, 1776, New Hampshire ratified the first state constitution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] New Jersey, South Carolina, and Virginia created their constitutions before July 4.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Rhode Island and Connecticut simply took their existing royal charters and deleted all references to the Crown.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The new states were all committed to republicanism, with no inherited offices.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The radical provisions of Pennsylvania's constitution lasted 14 years.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1790, conservatives gained power in the state legislature, called a new constitutional convention, and rewrote the constitution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The new constitution substantially reduced universal male suffrage, gave the governor veto power and patronage appointment authority, and added an upper house with substantial wealth qualifications to the unicameral legislature.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Thomas Paine called it a constitution unworthy of America.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In March 1776, aided by the fortification of Dorchester Heights with cannons recently captured at Fort Ticonderoga, the Continental Army led by George Washington forced the British to evacuate Boston.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries now fully controlled all thirteen states and ready to declare joint independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] There still were many Loyalists, but they were no longer in control anywhere by July 1776, and all of the royal officials had fled.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In April 1776, the North Carolina Provincial Congress issued the Halifax Resolves explicitly authorizing its delegates to vote for independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] By June, nine state legislatures supported independence from Britain, and Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, and New York followed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Richard Henry Lee was instructed by the Virginia legislature to propose independence, and he did so on June 7, 1776.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Gathered at Pennsylvania State House in Philadelphia, later renamed Independence Hall, 56 of the nation's Founding Fathers representing the United Colonies adopted and issued to King George III the Declaration of Independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] It had been drafted largely by Thomas Jefferson, and was edited and presented by the Committee of Five which was charged with authoring it.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Congress struck several provisions of the Committee's draft, and then adopted it unanimously on July 4.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Declaration embodied universal rights expressed through the political philosophies of liberalism and republicanism, rejected monarchy and aristocracy, and famously proclaimed that "all men are created equal".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] What had begun as a rebellion demanding the rights of Englishmen had now evolved into a revolution to overthrow and replace the political and social order in America based on universal rights.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] With the new state constitutions and the issuance of the Declaration of Independence, each former colony began operating as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The next step was to form a union to facilitate international relations and alliances.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On November 5, 1777, the Congress approved the Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union and sent it to each state for ratification.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Congress immediately began operating under the Articles' terms, providing a structure of shared sovereignty during prosecution of the Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Articles were fully ratified on March 1, 1781.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] At that point, the Continental Congress was dissolved and a new government of the United States in Congress Assembled took its place the following day, with Samuel Huntington leading the Congress as presiding officer.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] It remained a unicameral body, where each state retained one vote.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] According to British historian Jeremy Black, the British had significant advantages, including a highly trained army, the world's largest navy, and an efficient system of public finance that could easily fund the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] However, they seriously misunderstood the depth of support for the American Patriot position, misinterpreting the situation as merely a large-scale riot.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In the Siege of Boston, Washington forced the British out of the city in the spring of 1776, and neither the British nor the Loyalists controlled any significant areas.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British, however, were amassing forces at their naval base at Halifax, Nova Scotia.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They returned in force in July 1776, landing in New York and defeating Washington's Continental Army toe-to-toe in August at the Battle of Brooklyn, the largest battle of the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Following that victory, and poised to take New York City, they requested a meeting with representatives from Congress to negotiate an end to hostilities.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] A delegation including John Adams and Benjamin Franklin met British admiral Richard Howe on Staten Island in New York Harbor on September 11 in what became known as the Staten Island Peace Conference.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Howe demanded that the Americans retract the Declaration of Independence, which they refused to do, and negotiations ended.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British then seized New York City and nearly captured Washington's army.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They made the city their main political and military base of operations, holding the strategic harbor and port until November 1783.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The city became the destination for Loyalist refugees and a focal point of Washington's intelligence network.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British also took New Jersey, pushing the Continental Army into Pennsylvania.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Washington crossed the Delaware River back into New Jersey in a surprise attack in late December 1776 and defeated the Hessian and British garrisons at Trenton and Princeton, thereby regaining control of most of New Jersey.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The victories gave an important boost to Patriots at a time when morale was flagging and enlistments were ending, and they have become iconic events of the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1777, the British sent Burgoyne's invasion force from Canada south through New York with the aim of isolating New England to the east, which the British perceived as the primary source of agitation.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In anticipation of a coordinated British attack on the *de facto* revolutionary capital of Philadelphia, the Continental Congress was forced to temporarily depart Philadelphia in September for Baltimore, where they continued deliberations.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Rather than move north to support Burgoyne, the British army in New York City in fact went to Philadelphia in a major case of mis-coordination, capturing it from Washington.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The invasion army from Canada was much too slow and became trapped in northern New York state.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] It surrendered to the Americans after the Battles of Saratoga in October 1777.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] From early October 1777 until November 15, a siege distracted British troops at Fort Mifflin, Pennsylvania and allowed Washington time to preserve the Continental Army by safely leading his troops to harsh winter quarters at Valley Forge, some 35 miles from Philadelphia.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On August 23, 1775, George III declared Americans to be traitors to the Crown if they took up arms against royal authority.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] There were thousands of British and Hessian soldiers in American hands following their surrender at the Battles of Saratoga.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Lord Germain took a hard line, but the British generals on American soil never held treason trials, and instead treated captured American soldiers as prisoners of war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The dilemma was that tens of thousands of Loyalists were under American control and American retaliation would have been easy.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British built much of their strategy around using these Loyalists.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British maltreated the prisoners whom they held, resulting in more American deaths in the prisons than all the American battlefield mortalities, combined.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] At the end of the war, both sides released their surviving prisoners.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The capture of a British army at Saratoga encouraged the French to formally enter the war in support of Congress, and Benjamin Franklin negotiated a permanent military alliance in early 1778; France thus became the first foreign nation to officially recognize the Declaration of Independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On February 6, 1778, the United States and France signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce and the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] William Pitt spoke out in Parliament urging Britain to make peace with the Americans and to unite against France, while British politicians who had sympathized with colonial grievances now turned against the Americans for allying with Britain's rival and enemy.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Spanish and the Dutch became allies of the French in 1779 and 1780 respectively, forcing the British to fight a global war without major allies, and requiring it to slip through a combined blockade of the Atlantic.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Dutch Republic, also at war with Britain, was the next country after France to sign a treaty with the United States, on October 8, 1782.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On April 3, 1783, Ambassador Extraordinary Gustaf Philip Creutz, representing King Gustav III of Sweden, and Benjamin Franklin, signed a Treaty of Amity and Commerce with the U.S.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Britain began to view the American Revolutionary War as merely one front in a wider war, and the British chose to withdraw troops from America to reinforce the British colonies in the Caribbean, which were under threat of Spanish or French invasion.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] British commander Sir Henry Clinton evacuated Philadelphia and returned to New York City.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Washington intercepted him in the Battle of Monmouth Court House, the last major battle fought in the north.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] After an inconclusive engagement, the British retreated to New York City.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The northern war subsequently became a stalemate, as the focus of attention shifted to the smaller southern theater.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British Royal Navy blockaded ports and held New York City for the duration of the war, and other cities for brief periods, but failed in their effort to destroy Washington's forces.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British strategy now concentrated on a campaign in the southern states.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Due to a lack of regular troops at their disposal compared to the Americans, the British commanders saw the "southern strategy" as a more viable plan.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They perceived the Southern Colonies as strongly Loyalist, with a large population of recent British immigrants, and large numbers of slaves who might be tempted to run away from their Patriot masters to join the British and gain their freedom.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Beginning in late December 1778, the British captured Savannah and controlled the Georgia coastline.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In 1780, they launched a fresh invasion and took Charleston.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] A significant victory at the Battle of Camden meant that royal forces soon controlled most of Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British set up a network of forts inland, hoping that the Loyalists would rally to the flag.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Not enough Loyalists turned out, however, and the British had to fight their way north into North Carolina and Virginia with a severely weakened army.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Behind them, much of the territory that they had already captured dissolved into a chaotic guerrilla war, fought predominantly between bands of Loyalists and American militia, which negated many of the gains that the British had previously made.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British army under Cornwallis marched to Yorktown, Virginia, where they expected to be rescued by a British fleet.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The fleet did arrive, but so did a larger French fleet.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The French were victorious in the Battle of the Chesapeake, and the British fleet returned to New York for reinforcements, leaving Cornwallis trapped.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] In October 1781, the British surrendered their second invading army of the war under a siege by the combined French and Continental armies commanded by Washington.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Washington did not know if or when the British might reopen hostilities after Yorktown.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] They still had 26,000 troops occupying New York City, Charleston, and Savannah, together with a powerful fleet.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The French army and navy departed, so the Americans were on their own in 1782–83.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The American treasury was empty, and the unpaid soldiers were growing restive, almost to the point of mutiny or possible coup d'etat.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Washington dispelled the unrest among officers of the Newburgh Conspiracy in 1783, and Congress subsequently created the promise of a five years bonus for all officers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Historians continue to debate whether the odds were long or short for American victory.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Ferling says that the odds were so long that the American victory was "almost a miracle".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, Joseph Ellis says that the odds favored the Americans, and asks whether there ever was any realistic chance for the British to win.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] He argues that this opportunity came only once, in the summer of 1776, where Admiral Howe and his brother General Howe "missed several opportunities to destroy the Continental Army ....
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Chance, luck, and even the vagaries of the weather played crucial roles." Ellis's point is that the strategic and tactical decisions of the Howes were fatally flawed because they underestimated the challenges posed by the Patriots.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Ellis concludes that, once the Howe brothers failed, the opportunity "would never come again" for a British victory.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Public support for the conflict had never been strong in Britain, where many sympathized with the Americans, but now it reached a new low.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] King George wanted to fight on, but his supporters lost control of Parliament and the British launched no further offensives in America on the eastern seaboard.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] During negotiations in Paris, the American delegation discovered that France supported American independence but no territorial gains, hoping to confine the new nation to the area east of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The Americans opened direct secret negotiations with London, cutting out the French.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] British Prime Minister Lord Shelburne was in charge of the British negotiations, and he saw a chance to make the United States a valuable economic partner, facilitating trade and investment opportunities.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The US obtained all the land east of the Mississippi River, including southern Canada below the Great Lakes, but Spain took control of Florida from the British.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] It gained fishing rights off Canadian coasts, and agreed to allow British merchants and Loyalists to recover their property.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] Prime Minister Shelburne foresaw highly profitable two-way trade between Britain and the rapidly growing United States, which did come to pass.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The blockade was lifted and American merchants were free to trade with any nation anywhere in the world.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] The British largely abandoned their Indigenous allies, who were not a party to this treaty and did not recognize it until they were defeated militarily by the United States.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p01] However, the British did sell them munitions and maintained forts in American territory until the Jay Treaty of 1795.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Britain's war against the Americans, the French, and the Spanish cost about £100 million.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Treasury borrowed 40 percent of the money that it needed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Britain had a sophisticated financial system based on the wealth of thousands of landowners who supported the government, together with banks and financiers in London.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In London the British had relatively little difficulty financing their war, keeping their suppliers and soldiers paid, and hiring tens of thousands of German soldiers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In sharp contrast, Congress and the American states had no end of difficulty financing the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1775, there was at most 12 million dollars in gold in the colonies, not nearly enough to cover current transactions, let alone finance a major war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The British made the situation much worse by imposing a tight blockade on every American port, which cut off almost all trade.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] One partial solution was to rely on volunteer support from militiamen and donations from patriotic citizens.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Another was to delay actual payments, pay soldiers and suppliers in depreciated currency, and promise that it would be made good after the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Indeed, the soldiers and officers were given land grants in 1783 to cover the wages that they had earned but had not been paid during the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Starting in 1776, the Congress sought to raise money by loans from wealthy individuals, promising to redeem the bonds after the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The bonds were redeemed in 1791 at face value, but the scheme raised little money because Americans had little specie, and many of the richest merchants were supporters of the Crown.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Beginning in 1777, Congress repeatedly asked the states to provide money, but it had no system of taxation to require funds, and the states were of little help.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, Congress was making requisitions for specific supplies of corn, beef, pork, and other necessities, an inefficient system which barely kept the army alive.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Congress used four main methods to cover the cost of the war, which cost about 66 million dollars in specie (gold and silver).
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Significantly, the French secretly supplied the Americans with money, gunpowder, and munitions to weaken Great Britain; the subsidies continued when France entered the war in 1778, and the French government and Paris bankers lent large sums to the American war effort.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Congress also made issues of paper money, known colloquially as "Continental Dollars", in 1775–1780 and in 1780–1781.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The first issue amounted to 242 million dollars.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] This paper money would supposedly be redeemed for state taxes, but the holders were eventually paid off in 1791 at the rate of one cent on the dollar.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, the paper money was so devalued that the phrase "not worth a Continental" became synonymous with valueless.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The skyrocketing inflation was a hardship on the few people who had fixed incomes, but 90 percent of the people were farmers and were not directly affected by it.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Debtors benefited by paying off their debts with depreciated paper.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The greatest burden was borne by the soldiers of the Continental Army whose wages were usually paid late and depreciated in value every month, weakening their morale and adding to the hardships of their families.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The national government did not have a strong leader in financial matters until 1781, when Robert Morris was named Superintendent of Finance of the United States.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Morris used a French loan in 1782 to set up the private Bank of North America to finance the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] He reduced the civil list, saved money by using competitive bidding for contracts, tightened accounting procedures, and demanded the national government's full share of money and supplies from the individual states.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The war ended in 1783 and was followed by a period of slow economic recovery that accompanied the end of mercantilism and the resumption and expansion of worldwide trade.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The national government was still operating under the Articles of Confederation and settled the issue of the western territories, which the states ceded to Congress.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] American settlers moved rapidly into those areas, with Vermont, Kentucky, and Tennessee becoming states in the 1790s.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] However, the national government had no authority to tax, no money either to pay the war debts owed to European nations and the private banks, or to pay Americans who had been given millions of dollars of promissory notes for supplies during the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Nationalists led by Washington, Alexander Hamilton, and other veterans feared that the new nation was too fragile to withstand an international war, or even the repetition of internal revolts such as the Shays's Rebellion of 1786 in Massachusetts.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They convinced the Congress of the Confederation to call the Philadelphia Convention in 1787.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Convention adopted a new Constitution which provided for a republic with authority to tax and a much stronger national government in a federal framework, including an effective executive in a check-and-balance system with the judiciary and legislature.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Constitution was ratified in 1788, after a fierce debate in the states over the proposed new government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The new administration under President George Washington took office in New York in March 1789 and the new bicameral Congress of the United States was seated.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] James Madison spearheaded Congressional legislation proposing amendments to the Constitution as assurances to those cautious about federal power, guaranteeing many of the inalienable rights that formed a foundation for the revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Rhode Island was the final state to ratify the Constitution in 1790, the first ten amendments were ratified in 1791 and became known as the United States Bill of Rights.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The national debt fell into three categories after the Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The first was the $12 million owed to foreigners, mostly money borrowed from France.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] There was general agreement to pay the foreign debts at full value.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The national government owed $40 million and state governments owed $25 million to Americans who had sold food, horses, and supplies to the Patriot forces.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] There were also other debts which consisted of promissory notes issued during the war to soldiers, merchants, and farmers who accepted these payments on the premise that the new nation would create a government that would pay these debts eventually.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Americans struggled to pay off the French loans; they ceased making interest payments to France in 1785 and defaulted on installments due in 1787.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, however, they resumed regular payments on their debts to the French.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The war expenses of the individual states added up to $114 million, compared to $37 million by the central government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, Congress combined the remaining state debts with the foreign and domestic debts into one national debt totaling $80 million at the recommendation of first Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Everyone received face value for wartime certificates, so that the national honor would be sustained and the national credit established.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Accounts with the French government were settled in 1795 when James Swan, an American banker acting as agent for France, helped refinance the United States’ remaining debt to France.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The American government issued bonds in the amount of the remaining debt and sold them publicly, with the proceeds going to France through Swan.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The United States no longer owed money to foreign governments, although it continued to owe money to private investors both in the United States and in Europe..
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] This allowed the young United States to place itself on a sound financial footing.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The population of the Thirteen States was not homogeneous in political views and attitudes.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Loyalties and allegiances varied widely within regions and communities and even within families, and sometimes shifted during the Revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The American Enlightenment was a critical precursor of the American Revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Chief among the ideas of the American Enlightenment were the concepts of natural law, natural rights, consent of the governed, self-determination, equality under the law, liberalism, republicanism, and intolerance of political corruption.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] A growing number of American colonists embraced these views and fostered an intellectual environment which led to a new sense of political and social identity.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] John Locke is often referred to as "the philosopher of the American Revolution" due to his work in the Social Contract and Natural Rights theories that underpinned the Revolution's political ideology.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Locke's *Two Treatises of Government* published in 1689 was especially influential.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] He argued that all humans were created equally free, and governments therefore needed the "consent of the governed".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] This contrasted and conflicted sharply with the British system of inherited political power and hierarchy.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In late eighteenth-century America, belief was still widespread in "equality by creation" and "rights by creation".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Locke's ideas on liberty influenced the political thinking of English writers such as John Trenchard, Thomas Gordon, and Benjamin Hoadly, whose political ideas in turn also had a strong influence on the American Patriots.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] His work also inspired symbols used in the American Revolution such as the "Appeal to Heaven" found on the Pine Tree Flag, which alludes to Locke's concept of the right of revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The theory of the social contract influenced the belief among many of the Founders that the right of the people to overthrow their leaders, should those leaders betray the historic rights of Englishmen, was one of the "natural rights" of man.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Americans heavily relied on Montesquieu's analysis of the wisdom of the "balanced" British Constitution (mixed government) in writing the state and national constitutions.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The American interpretation of republicanism was inspired by the Whig party in Great Britain which openly criticized the corruption within the British government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Americans were increasingly embracing republican values, seeing Britain as corrupt and hostile to American interests.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Radical Whig ideology profoundly influenced colonial American political philosophy with its love of liberty and opposition to tyrannical government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The American revolutionaries associated political corruption with ostentatious luxury and inherited aristocracy.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Founding Fathers were strong advocates of republican values, particularly Samuel Adams, Patrick Henry, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Thomas Jefferson, Thomas Paine, George Washington, James Madison, and Alexander Hamilton, which required men to put civic duty ahead of their personal desires.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Men were honor bound by civic obligation to be prepared and willing to fight for the rights and liberties of their countrymen.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Protestant churches that had separated from the Church of England, called "dissenters", were the "school of democracy", in the words of historian Patricia Bonomi.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Before the Revolution, the Southern Colonies and three of the New England Colonies had official established churches: Congregational in Massachusetts Bay, Connecticut, and New Hampshire, and the Church of England in Maryland, Virginia, North-Carolina, South Carolina, and Georgia.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The colonies of New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, and the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations had no officially established churches.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] John Witherspoon, who was considered a "new light" Presbyterian, wrote widely circulated sermons linking the American Revolution to the teachings of the Bible.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Throughout the colonies, dissenting Protestant ministers from the Congregational, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches preached Revolutionary themes in their sermons while most Church of England clergymen preached loyalty to the king, the titular head of the English state church.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Religious motivation for fighting tyranny transcended socioeconomic lines.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Historian Bernard Bailyn argues that the evangelicalism of the era challenged traditional notions of natural hierarchy by preaching that the Bible teaches all men are equal, and the true value of a man therefore lies in his moral behavior, not in his class.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Bailyn, on the other hand, denies that religion played such a critical role.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Alan Heimert argues that New Light anti-authoritarianism was essential to furthering democracy in colonial American society, and set the stage for a confrontation with British monarchical and aristocratic rule.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Historians in the early 20th century such as J.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Franklin Jameson examined the class composition of the Patriot cause, looking for evidence of a class war inside the revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] More recent historians have largely abandoned that interpretation, emphasizing instead the high level of ideological unity.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Both Loyalists and Patriots were a "mixed lot", but ideological demands always came first.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The revolution became a personal issue for the king, fueled by his growing belief that British leniency would be taken as weakness by the Americans.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] He also sincerely believed that he was defending Britain's constitution against usurpers, rather than opposing patriots fighting for their natural rights.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] King George III is often accused of obstinately trying to keep Great Britain at war with the revolutionaries in America, despite the opinions of his own ministers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Later historians defend George by saying in the context of the times no king would willingly surrender such a large territory, and his conduct was far less ruthless than contemporary monarchs in Europe.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] After the surrender of a British army at Saratoga, both Parliament and the British people were largely in favor of the war; recruitment ran at high levels and although political opponents were vocal, they remained a small minority.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] With the early setbacks in America, Lord North asked to transfer power to Lord Chatham, whom he thought more capable, but George refused to do so; he suggested instead that Chatham serve as a subordinate minister in North's administration, but Chatham refused.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Lord North was allied to the "King's Friends" faction in Parliament and believed George III had the right to exercise extensive powers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In early 1778, Britain's chief rival France signed a treaty of alliance with the United States, and the confrontation soon escalated from a "rebellion" to something that has been characterized as "world war".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The French fleet was able to outrun the British naval blockade of the Mediterranean and sailed to North America.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The conflict now affected North America, Europe and India.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The United States and France were joined by Spain in 1779 and the Dutch Republic, while Britain had no major allies of its own, except for the Loyalist minority in America and German auxiliaries (i.e.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Lord Gower and Lord Weymouth both resigned from the government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Lord North again requested that he also be allowed to resign, but he stayed in office at George III's insistence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Opposition to the costly war was increasing, and in June 1780 contributed to disturbances in London known as the Gordon riots.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] As late as the Siege of Charleston in 1780, Loyalists could still believe in their eventual victory, as British troops inflicted defeats on the Continental forces at the Battle of Camden and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In late 1781, the news of Cornwallis's surrender at the siege of Yorktown reached London; Lord North's parliamentary support ebbed away and he resigned the following year.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The king drafted an abdication notice, which was never delivered, finally accepted the defeat in North America, and authorized peace negotiations.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Treaties of Paris, by which Britain recognized the sovereignty of the United States and returned Florida to Spain, were signed in 1782 and 1783 respectively.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In early 1783, George III privately conceded "America is lost!" He reflected that the former colonies had developed into Britain's "successful rivals" in commercial trade and fishing as the United States.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] When John Adams was appointed American Minister to London in 1785, George had become resigned to the new relationship between his country and the former colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Those who fought for independence were called "Revolutionaries", "Continentals", "Rebels", "Patriots", "Whigs", "Congress-men", or "Americans" during and after the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They included a full range of social and economic classes but were unanimous regarding the need to defend the natural rights of Americans and uphold the principles of republicanism in rejecting monarchy and aristocracy, while emphasizing civic virtue by citizens.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The signers of the Declaration of Independence were overwhelmingly—with definite exceptions—well-educated, of British stock, and of the Protestant faith.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Newspapers were strongholds of patriotism (although there were a few Loyalist papers) and printed many pamphlets, announcements, patriotic letters, and pronouncements.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] According to historian Robert Calhoon, 40 to 45 percent of the white population in the Thirteen Colonies supported the Patriots' cause, 15 to 20 percent supported the Loyalists, and the remainder were neutral or kept a low profile.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Mark Lender concludes that ordinary people became insurgents against the British because they held a sense of rights which the British were violating, rights that stressed local autonomy, fair dealing, and government by consent.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They were highly sensitive to the issue of tyranny, which they saw manifested in the British response to the Boston Tea Party.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The arrival in Boston of the British Army heightened their sense of violated rights, leading to rage and demands for revenge.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They had faith that God was on their side.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Patriots viewed independence as a means to gain freedom from British oppression and initially to reassert their rights on par with subjects in Britain.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Most yeomen farmers, craftsmen, and small merchants joined the Patriot cause to demand more political equality.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They were especially successful in Pennsylvania but less so in New England, where John Adams attacked Thomas Paine's *Common Sense* for the "absurd democratical notions" that it proposed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Thomas Paine published his pamphlet *Common Sense* in January 1776, after the Revolution had started.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] It was widely distributed and often read aloud in taverns, contributing significantly to concurrently spreading the ideas of republicanism and liberalism, bolstering enthusiasm for separation from Great Britain, and encouraging recruitment for the Continental Army.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Paine presented the Revolution as the solution for Americans alarmed by the threat of tyranny.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The consensus of scholars is that about 15 to 20 percent of the white population remained loyal to the British Crown.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Those who actively supported the king were known at the time as "Loyalists", "Tories", or "King's men".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Loyalists never controlled territory unless the British Army occupied it.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They were typically older, less willing to break with old loyalties, and often connected to the Church of England; they included many established merchants with strong business connections throughout the Empire, as well as royal officials such as Thomas Hutchinson of Boston.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In the mid-20th century, historian Leonard Woods Labaree identified eight characteristics of the Loyalists that made them essentially conservative, opposite to the characteristics of the Patriots.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists tended to feel that resistance to the Crown was morally wrong, while the Patriots thought that morality was on their side.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists were alienated when the Patriots resorted to violence, such as burning houses and tarring and feathering.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists wanted to take a centrist position and resisted the Patriots' demand to declare their opposition to the Crown.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Numerous Loyalists had maintained strong and long-standing relations with Britain, especially merchants in port cities such as New York and Boston.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists felt that independence was bound to come eventually, but they were fearful that revolution might lead to anarchy, tyranny, or mob rule.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In contrast, the prevailing attitude among Patriots was a desire to seize the initiative.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Labaree also contended that Loyalists were pessimists who lacked the confidence in the future displayed by the Patriots.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] There were "tens of thousands" of Black Loyalists, enslaved African Americans who escaped to British lines and supported Britain's cause via several means.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Many of them died from disease, but the survivors were evacuated by the British to their remaining colonies in North America.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The revolution could divide families, such as William Franklin, son of Benjamin Franklin and royal governor of the Province of New Jersey who remained loyal to the Crown throughout the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Recent immigrants who had not been fully Americanized were also inclined to support the King.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] After the war, the great majority of the half-million Loyalists remained in America and resumed normal lives.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Some became prominent American leaders, such as Samuel Seabury.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Approximately 46,000 Loyalists relocated to Canada; others moved to Britain (7,000), Florida, or the West Indies (9,000).
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The exiles represented approximately two percent of the total population of the colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Nearly all Black Loyalists left for Nova Scotia, Florida, or England, where they could remain free.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists who left the South in 1783 took thousands of enslaved persons with them as they fled to the British West Indies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] A minority of uncertain size tried to stay neutral in the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Most kept a low profile, but the Quakers were the most important group to speak out for neutrality, especially in Pennsylvania.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Quakers continued to do business with the British even after the war began, and they were accused of supporting British rule, "contrivers and authors of seditious publications" critical of the revolutionary cause.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Most Quakers remained neutral, although a sizeable number participated to some degree.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Women contributed to the American Revolution in many ways and were involved on both sides.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Formal politics did not include women, but ordinary domestic behaviors became charged with political significance as Patriot women confronted a war which permeated all aspects of political, civil, and domestic life.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They participated by boycotting British goods, spying on the British, following armies as they marched, washing, cooking, and mending for soldiers, delivering secret messages, and even fighting disguised as men in a few cases, such as Deborah Samson.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Mercy Otis Warren held meetings in her house and cleverly attacked Loyalists with her creative plays and histories.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Many women also acted as nurses and helpers, tending to the soldiers' wounds and buying and selling goods for them.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Some of these camp followers even participated in combat, such as Madam John Turchin who led her husband's regiment into battle.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Above all, women continued the agricultural work at home to feed their families and the armies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They maintained their families during their husbands' absences and sometimes after their deaths.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] American women were integral to the success of the boycott of British goods, as the boycotted items were largely household articles such as tea and cloth.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Women had to return to knitting goods and to spinning and weaving their own cloth—skills that had fallen into disuse.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1769, the women of Boston produced 40,000 skeins of yarn, and 180 women in Middletown, Massachusetts wove 20,522 yards (18,765 m) of cloth.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Many women gathered food, money, clothes, and other supplies during the war to help the soldiers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] A woman's loyalty to her husband could become an open political act, especially for women in America committed to men who remained loyal to the King.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Legal divorce, usually rare, was granted to Patriot women whose husbands supported the King.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In early 1776, France set up a major program of aid to the Americans, and the Spanish secretly added funds.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Each country spent one million "livres tournaises" to buy munitions.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] A dummy corporation run by Pierre Beaumarchais concealed their activities.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots obtained some munitions from the Dutch Republic as well, through the French and Spanish ports in the West Indies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Heavy expenditures and a weak taxation system pushed France toward bankruptcy.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1777, Charles François Adrien le Paulmier, Chevalier d'Annemours, acting as a secret agent for France, made sure General George Washington was privy to his mission.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] He followed Congress around for the next two years, reporting what he observed back to France.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Treaty of Alliance between the French and the Americans followed in 1778, which led to more French money, matériel and troops being sent to the United States.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Spain did not officially recognize the United States, but it was a French ally and it separately declared war on Britain on June 21, 1779.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Bernardo de Gálvez, general of the Spanish forces in New Spain bordering the Americans, also served as governor of Louisiana.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] He led an expedition of colonial troops to capture Florida from the British and to keep open a vital conduit for supplies going to the Americans.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Ethnic Germans served on both sides of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] As George III was also the Elector of Hanover, many supported the Loyalist cause and served as allies of the Kingdom of Great Britain; most notably rented auxiliary troops from German states such as the Landgraviate of Hessen-Kassel.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots tended to represent such troops as mercenaries in propaganda against the British Crown.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Even American historians followed suit, in spite of Colonial-era jurists drawing a distinction between auxiliaries and mercenaries, with auxiliaries serving their prince when sent to the aid of another prince, and mercenaries serving a foreign prince as individuals.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] By this distinction the troops which served in the American Revolution were auxiliaries.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Other German individuals came to assist the American revolutionaries, most notably Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben, who served as a general in the Continental Army and is credited with professionalizing that force, but most Germans who served were already colonists.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Von Steuben's native Prussia joined the League of Armed Neutrality, and King Frederick II of Prussia was well appreciated in the United States for his support early in the war.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] He expressed interest in opening trade with the United States and bypassing English ports, and allowed an American agent to buy arms in Prussia.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Frederick predicted American success, and promised to recognize the United States and American diplomats once France did the same.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Prussia also interfered in the recruiting efforts of Russia and neighboring German states when they raised armies to send to the Americas, and Frederick II forbade enlistment for the American war within Prussia.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] All Prussian roads were denied to troops from Anhalt-Zerbst, which delayed reinforcements that Howe had hoped to receive during the winter of 1777–1778.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] However, when the War of the Bavarian Succession (1778–1779) erupted, Frederick II became much more cautious with Prussian/British relations.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] U.S. ships were denied access to Prussian ports, and Frederick refused to officially recognize the United States until they had signed the Treaty of Paris.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Even after the war, Frederick II predicted that the United States was too large to operate as a republic, and that it would soon rejoin the British Empire with representatives in Parliament.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Most Indigenous people rejected pleas that they remain neutral and instead supported the British Crown.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The great majority of the ~200,000 indigenous people east of the Mississippi distrusted the Americans and supported the British cause, hoping to forestall continued expansion of settlement into their territories.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Those tribes closely involved in trade tended to side with the Patriots, although political factors were important as well.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Some tried to remain neutral, seeing little value in joining what they perceived to be a "white man's war", and fearing reprisals from whichever side they opposed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The British did have other indigenous allies, particularly in the regions of southwest Quebec on the Patriot's frontier.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The British provided arms to Indigenous people who were led by Loyalists in war parties to raid frontier settlements from the Carolinas to New York.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] These war parties killed many settlers on the frontier, especially in western Pennsylvania and New York's Mohawk Valley.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1776, Cherokee war parties attacked American settlers all along the southern Quebec frontier of the uplands throughout the Washington District, North Carolina (now Tennessee) and the Kentucky wilderness area.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Chickamauga Cherokee under Tsiyu Gansini (*also* Dragging Canoe) allied themselves closely with the British, and fought on for an additional decade after the Treaty of Paris was signed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They launched raids with roughly 200 warriors, as seen in the Cherokee–American wars; they could not mobilize enough forces to invade settler areas without the help of allies, most often the Creek.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Joseph Brant (*also* Thayendanegea), from the powerful Mohawk tribe of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy, was the most prominent Indigenous leader against the Patriot forces.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1778 and 1780, he led 300 Iroquois warriors and 100 white Loyalists in multiple attacks on small frontier settlements in New York and Pennsylvania, killing many settlers and destroying villages, crops, and food stockpiles.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In 1779, the Continental Army forced the hostile Indigenous people out of upstate New York when Washington sent an army under John Sullivan which destroyed 40 evacuated Iroquois villages in central and western New York.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The Battle of Newtown proved decisive, as the Patriots had an advantage of three-to-one, and it ended significant resistance; there was little combat otherwise.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Facing starvation and homeless for the winter, the Iroquois that allied with the British fled to Canada.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] At the peace conference following the war, the British ceded lands which they did not really control, without consultation with their Indigenous allies that inhabited them.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They transferred control to the United States of all the land south of the Great Lakes east of the Mississippi and north of Florida.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The existence of slavery in the American colonies had attracted criticism from both sides of the Atlantic as many could not reconcile the existence of the institution with the egalitarian ideals espoused by leaders of the Revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The English writer Samuel Johnson wrote "how is it we hear the loudest yelps for liberty among the drivers of the Negroes?" in a text opposing the grievances of the colonists.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Crispus Attucks, of mixed racial heritage, was one of the five people killed in the Boston Massacre in 1770 and is considered the first American casualty for the cause of independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Free Blacks in the New England Colonies and Middle Colonies in the North as well as Southern Colonies fought on both sides of the War, but the majority fought for the Patriots.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Gary Nash reports that there were about 9,000 Black veteran Patriots, counting the Continental Army and Navy, state militia units, privateers, wagoneers in the Army, servants to officers, and spies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The effects of the war were more dramatic in the South.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Tens of thousands of enslaved persons escaped to British lines throughout the South, causing dramatic losses to slaveholders and disrupting cultivation and harvesting of crops.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] For instance, South Carolina was estimated to have lost about 25,000 enslaved persons to flight, migration, or death which amounted to a third of its enslaved population.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] As noted by the historian Karen Cook Bell, during the Revolutionary War roughly one-third of all the escaped enslaved were women, even though prior to 1775 nearly 87% had been men.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] During the war, British commanders attempted to weaken the Patriots by issuing proclamations of freedom to their enslaved.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] In the November 1775 document known as Dunmore's Proclamation Virginia royal governor, Lord Dunmore recruited Black men for British military service with the promise of freedom, protection for their families, and land grants.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Hundreds of Black men responded and were formed into the Royal Ethiopian Regiment.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Colonists, primarily Southern Patriots, were deeply angered by Dunmore's proclamation, which spread through all of the Thirteen Colonies and threatened to upturn the existing American racial hierarchy; it also played a major role in Southern support for American independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Accusations that the British were encouraging slave rebellions were prominent features of Patriot propaganda, with Jefferson even accusing George III in the 27 colonial grievances of having "excited domestic Insurrections among us".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] The 1779 Philipsburg Proclamation expanded the promise of freedom for Black men who enlisted in the British military to all the colonies in rebellion.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] At the conclusion of the war, British forces gave transportation to 10,000 of the formerly enslaved when they evacuated Savannah and Charles Town, carrying through on their promise.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] They evacuated and resettled more than 3,000 Black Loyalists from New York to Nova Scotia, Upper Canada, and Lower Canada.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Others sailed with the British to England or were resettled as freedmen in the West Indies of the Caribbean.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] But the enslaved carried to the Caribbean under control of Loyalist masters generally remained enslaved until the British abolition of slavery in its colonies in 1833–1838.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] More than 1,200 of the Black Loyalists of Nova Scotia later resettled in the British colony of Sierra Leone in Africa, where they became leaders of the Krio ethnic group of Freetown and the later national government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Many of their descendants still live in Sierra Leone, as well as other African countries.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Despite the turmoil of the period, African-Americans contributed to the foundation of an American national identity during the Revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p02] Phyllis Wheatley, an African American poet, popularized the image of Columbia to represent America.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] After the Revolution, genuinely democratic politics became possible in the former American colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The rights of the people were incorporated into state constitutions.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Concepts of liberty, consent of the governed, individual rights, equality and due process under the law, and intolerance of corruption became incorporated as core values of liberal republicanism.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The new United States government was empowered to undertake its own project of territorial expansion and settler colonialism.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The greatest challenge to the old order in Europe was the challenge to inherited political power and the democratic idea that government rests on the consent of the governed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Losing the war and the Thirteen Colonies was a shock to Britain.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The war revealed the limitations of Britain's fiscal-military state when they discovered that they suddenly faced powerful enemies with no allies, and they were dependent on extended and vulnerable transatlantic lines of communication.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The defeat heightened dissension and escalated political antagonism to the king's ministers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The king went so far as to draft letters of abdication, although they were never delivered.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Inside Parliament, the primary concern changed from fears of an over-mighty monarch to the issues of representation, parliamentary reform, and government retrenchment.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Unable to accept loss of the war and the colonies as possibly due to anything else but widespread institutional corruption, reformers sought to root it out, and the result was a crisis from 1776 to 1783.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The crisis ended after 1784 confidence in the British constitution was restored during the administration of Prime Minister William Pitt.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution ended an age—an age of monarchy.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] And, it began a new age—an age of freedom.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] As a result of the growing wave started by the Revolution, there are now more people around the world living in freedom than ever before, both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of the world's population.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Interpretations vary concerning the effect of the Revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Historians such as Bernard Bailyn, Gordon Wood, and Edmund Morgan view it as a unique and radical event which produced deep changes and had a profound effect on world affairs, such as an increasing belief in the principles of the Enlightenment.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] These were demonstrated by a leadership and government that espoused protection of natural rights, and a system of laws chosen by the people.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] John Murrin, by contrast, argues that the definition of "the people" at that time was mostly restricted to free men who passed a property qualification.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The first shot of the American Revolution at the Battle of Lexington and Concord is referred to as the "shot heard 'round the world".
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution was the first of the Atlantic Revolutions: followed most notably by the French Revolution, the Haitian Revolution, and the Latin American wars of independence.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Aftershocks contributed to rebellions in Ireland, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, and the Netherlands.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Constitution, drafted shortly after independence, remains the world's oldest written constitution, and has been emulated by other countries, in some cases verbatim.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Some historians and scholars argue that the subsequent wave of independence and revolutionary movements has contributed to the continued expansion of democratic government; 144 countries, representing two-third of the world's population, are full or partially democracies of some form.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution had a strong, immediate influence in Great Britain, Ireland, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Many British and Irish Whigs in Parliament spoke glowingly in favor of the American cause.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In Ireland, the Protestant minority who controlled Ireland demanded self-rule.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Under the leadership of Henry Grattan, the Irish Patriot Party forced the reversal of mercantilist prohibitions against trade with other British colonies.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The King and his cabinet in London could not risk another rebellion, and so made a series of concessions to the Patriot faction in Dublin.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Armed volunteer units of the *Protestant Ascendancy* were set up ostensibly to protect against an invasion from France.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] As had been in colonial America, so too in Ireland now the King no longer had a monopoly of lethal force.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] By 1798, the Irish were ready for a republican uprising.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] For many Europeans, such as the Marquis de Lafayette, who later were active during the era of the French Revolution, the American case along with the Dutch Revolt (end of the 16th century) and the 17th century English Civil War, was among the examples of overthrowing an old regime.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The American Declaration of Independence influenced the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen of 1789.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The spirit of the Declaration of Independence led to laws ending slavery in all the Northern states and the Northwest Territory, with New Jersey the last in 1804.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] States such as New Jersey and New York adopted gradual emancipation, which kept some people as slaves for more than two decades longer.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] During the revolution, the contradiction between the Patriots' professed ideals of liberty and the institution of slavery generated increased scrutiny of the latter.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] As early as 1764, the Boston Patriot leader James Otis, Jr. declared that all men, "white or black", were "by the law of nature" born free.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Anti-slavery calls became more common in the early 1770s.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In 1773, Benjamin Rush, the future signer of the Declaration of Independence, called on "advocates for American liberty" to oppose slavery.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Slavery became an issue that had to be addressed.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In the late 1760s and early 1770s, several colonies, including Massachusetts and Virginia, attempted to restrict the slave trade, but were prevented from doing so by royally appointed governors.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In 1774, as part of a broader non-importation movement aimed at Britain, the Continental Congress called on all the colonies to ban the importation of enslaved people, and the colonies passed acts doing so.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In the first two decades after the American Revolution, state legislatures and individuals took actions to free the enslaved, in part based on Revolutionary ideals.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Northern states passed new constitutions that contained language about equal rights or specifically abolished slavery; some states, such as New York and New Jersey, where slavery was more widespread, passed laws by the end of the 18th century to abolish slavery by a gradual method.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] By 1804, all the northern states had passed laws outlawing slavery, either immediately or over time.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] However, enslavers could grant freedom to individuals they enslaved.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Numerous slaveholders who freed their enslaved cited Revolutionary ideals in their documents; others freed their enslaved as a reward for service.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Records also suggest that some slaveholders were freeing their own mixed-race children, born to enslaved mothers.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The number of free Blacks as a proportion of the Black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, slavery continued in the South, where it was protected as a "peculiar institution", setting the stage for future sectional conflict between North and South over the issue.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Thousands of free Blacks in the northern states fought in the state militias and Continental Army.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In the south, both sides offered freedom to slaves who would perform military service.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Roughly 20,000 enslaved persons fought in the American Revolution.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] While women were entering a period in which they found themselves gaining more identity within society, it was clear that they were still very much considered under men as their role in society remained being a good wife and mother.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Having a woman who was dressed well for her role as a good wife and mother as well as fitting the social role, was a symbol of not only status, but a family devoted to the republic.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] As they continued to nurture social and political partnerships, their role in enabling the success of the revolution emphasized their changing role in society – leading to the post-revolutionary reconstruction of gender ideology.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In addition, the democratic ideals of the Revolution inspired changes in the roles of women.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Patriot women married to Loyalists who left the state could get a divorce and obtain control of the ex-husband's property.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] As discussions rose regarding the rights of man post Revolutionary war, women began pushing a debate for the rights of women as well.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Mary Wollstonecraft pioneered the discussion regarding women's rights, and push those like Abigail Adams to begin expressing the desire to want a larger place in society.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Wollstonecraft was an English writer, philosopher, and advocate for women's rights, and would publish the *Vindication of the Rights of Woman* (1792) – challenging the idea that rights should only be granted to men.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Her radical ideas would give ground to the conversation in allowing women to be bearers of rights alongside men – that while the rights of man were taking on a new meaning post-revolutionary America, it was time for the rights of women too.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Inspired by the radical feminism in her work, women in the early republic would change their views on marriage, education, participation in public life, and autonomy – pushing them to lay the groundwork for the later women's suffrage movement, education opportunities, property rights, and more.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] However, this new sense of independence and dignity did not come with ease, as a gender hierarchy would continue to bind what it meant for women to have rights during the post-revolutionary era.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Women in the early republic had many limitations – they could not vote, hold political office, earn fair wages, lacked opportunities for higher education and certain professions, and most importantly, own property independently of their husbands.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] In addition, they held little legal powers in subjects such as divorce, property rights, and child custody.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] A central legal concept that reinforced these restrictions was *coverture*, a central legal doctrine that limited women's lives in all aspects – making a woman's legal identity a part of their husband's.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The early national period of America would continue to struggle with the concept of rights and equality.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Tens of thousands of Loyalists left the United States following the war; Philip Ranlet estimates 20,000, while Maya Jasanoff estimates as many as 70,000.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Some migrated to Britain, but the great majority received land and subsidies for resettlement in British colonies in North America, especially Quebec (concentrating in the Eastern Townships), Prince Edward Island, and Nova Scotia.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Britain created the colonies of Upper Canada (Ontario) and New Brunswick expressly for their benefit, and the Crown awarded land to Loyalists as compensation for losses in the United States.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Nevertheless, approximately eighty-five percent of the Loyalists stayed in the United States as American citizens, and some of the exiles later returned to the U.S.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Patrick Henry spoke of the issue of allowing Loyalists to return as such: "Shall we, who have laid the proud British lion at our feet, be frightened of its whelps?" His actions helped secure return of the Loyalists to American soil.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution has a central place in the American memory as the story of the nation's founding.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] It is covered in the schools, memorialized by two national holidays, Washington's Birthday in February and Independence Day in July, and commemorated in innumerable monuments.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] George Washington's estate at Mount Vernon was one of the first national pilgrimages for tourists and attracted 10,000 visitors a year by the 1850s.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution became a matter of contention in the 1850s in the debates leading to the American Civil War (1861–1865), as spokesmen of both the Northern United States and the Southern United States claimed that their region was the true custodian of the legacy of 1776.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The United States Bicentennial in 1976 came a year after the American withdrawal from the Vietnam War, and speakers stressed the themes of renewal and rebirth based on a restoration of traditional values.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] Today, more than 100 battlefields and historic sites of the American Revolution are protected and maintained by the government.
[src:american-revolution/american-revolution-p03] The National Park Service alone manages and maintains more than 50 battlefield parks and many other sites such as Independence Hall that are related to the Revolution.
